ce:section.ce:para:
Portable optofluidic and flexible hydrogel biosensors can also offer easy-to-handle, low-cost and disposable glucose strips (Yin et al., 2016; Yetisen et al., 2017). The synergistic assembly of photonic fibres and microfluidics enabled the fabrication of portable lab-on-a-chip devices (Scheme 7
                        ) (Yin et al., 2016). Meanwhile, the flexible hydrogel optical fibres enabled the fabrication of insertable needle device settings on porcine tissue (Scheme 8
                        ) (Yetisen et al., 2017). Optic fibre device patterns were built by the functionalisation of polymeric-layered films and then GOD and PBA along the fibre optics of long-period grating and flexible hydrogels, respectively (Yin et al., 2016; Yetisen et al., 2017). Such fibre optofluidic and hydrogel needle devices enabled changes in refractive index and light transmission properties during the binding with glucose. Results indicated that the integration of optical fibre biosensors into a portable microfluidic chipset leads to the quick and ultra-sensitive determination of ultra-trace glucose levels (Scheme 7) (Yin et al., 2016). The optical visualisation pattern of flexible hydrogel fibres is controlled by embedding the red and green fluorescent beads to the inner core and the outer cladding (Scheme 8C) (Yetisen et al., 2017). The flexible optical hydrogel fibre was modified to mimic thin hypodermic needles as insertable and implantable devices for the easy-handling and label-free optical sensing of glucose levels (Scheme 8D) (Shukla et al., 2017).

With the progress of wearable/implantable optical fibre glucose sensors, smartphone-incorporated flexible and optic hydrogel fibre biosensors were designed to enable easy-to-read output signals of responsive and selective glucose physiological samples. In this regard, thin light-transmitting, biocompatible, optical glucose fibres were fabricated by imprinting hydrogel with asymmetric micro-lens array, which is significantly connected to a multimedia silica fibre tip during the photo-polymerisation of its surface topographies (Scheme 9
                        A,B) (Elsherif et al., 2019). The readable signal output of biocompatible fibre glucose optodes was developed and monitored on the screen display of smartphones, thereby allowing well-controlled optical power assessment assays. This sensory glucose device provides continuous glucose visualisation assays for the on-time monitoring, fast response and sensitive and selective detection of glucose in physiological fluids (Scheme 9
                        ) (Elsherif et al., 2019).

Overall, diverse nano- and micro-materials with different sizes, shapes and surface functionalities were used as potential components in the design of flexible device layouts and chipsets (Scheme 10). For instance, applicable sensor array platforms based on hydrophilic hydrogel polymers were applied on harmless, soft and mechanically stable and flexible devices. Several studies introduced diverse types of popular composite or hybrid materials which feature long-term and biocompatible skin-, epidermis-, or human-friendly microelectronics and facile electron/charge transfer surfaces to provide conformal full-package wearable systems (Kim et al., 2018b; Mostafalu et al., 2016; Lim et al., 2020). Prospective and applicable nano- and micro-materials used into wearable sensing layouts are still required to provide unique skin devices with the following multifunctional keys and smart workability features:

                           (i)

to protect the epidermis from burning after multi-sensing assays at active sampling layers;


                           (ii)

to inhibit any skin inflammatory or toxicity due to the potential pH changes or non-preferable sample leakage during analysis;


                           (iii)

to provide facile yet efficient glucose collection without inter-sampling interferences;


                           (iv)

to create a built-in system with contentious sample diffusion;


                           (v)

to suppress the wearable device layout deformation or defects (i.e. cracks or damages) from mechanical strains, including bending, twisting and stretching, during multiple analyses;


                           (vi)

to offer biocompatible and toxicological CGM systems in both sensing assays of in vitro and in vivo analyses; and


                           (vii)

to help stabilise the dynamic device linearity in terms of gauge signalling and sensing accuracy under applied condition strains, such as high humidity and temperature, and photo- and bio-degradation.
